ğŸ” 1. Create a Secret in Kubernetes

Secrets are used to store sensitive data like passwords, tokens, keys.

ğŸ‘‰ Create Secret using kubectl command

kubectl create secret generic db-secret \
  --from-literal=DB_USER=admin \
  --from-literal=DB_PASSWORD=Admin@123

ğŸ‘‰ Verify Secret

kubectl get secrets
kubectl describe secret db-secret

ğŸ‘‰ Use Secret inside a Pod (Env variables)

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: secret-demo-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx
    env:
    - name: DB_USER
      valueFrom:
        secretKeyRef:
          name: db-secret
          key: DB_USER
    - name: DB_PASSWORD
      valueFrom:
        secretKeyRef:
          name: db-secret
          key: DB_PASSWORD


Apply:

kubectl apply -f secret-pod.yaml

âš™ï¸ 2. Create a ConfigMap in Kubernetes

ConfigMaps store non-sensitive configuration like env values, URLs, ports.

4
ğŸ‘‰ Create ConfigMap using command
kubectl create configmap app-config \
  --from-literal=APP_ENV=production \
  --from-literal=APP_PORT=8080

ğŸ‘‰ Verify ConfigMap
kubectl get configmaps
kubectl describe configmap app-config

ğŸ‘‰ Use ConfigMap in Pod
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: configmap-demo-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx
    envFrom:
    - configMapRef:
        name: app-config


Apply:

kubectl apply -f configmap-pod.yaml

ğŸ§¾ 3. Create a Job in Kubernetes

Jobs are used for one-time tasks like:

DB migration

Backup

Batch processing

Report generation

4
ğŸ‘‰ Job Example (Print message and exit)
apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: Job
metadata:
  name: job-demo
spec:
  completions: 1
  backoffLimit: 3
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: job-container
        image: busybox
        command: ["sh", "-c", "echo Job Completed Successfully"]
      restartPolicy: Never


Apply:

kubectl apply -f job.yaml

ğŸ‘‰ Check Job Status
kubectl get jobs
kubectl get pods
kubectl logs <job-pod-name>
